[2;36m╭─[0m[2;36m────────────────────────────────────[0m[2;36m [0m[1;2;36mLLM Thinking[0m[2;36m [0m[2;36m────────────────────────────────────[0m[2;36m─╮[0m
[2;36m│[0m Now I see the pattern more clearly:                                                    [2;36m│[0m
[2;36m│[0m                                                                                        [2;36m│[0m
[2;36m│[0m 1. **Safe text + form-urlencoded** → Error message with "safe_text" reflected          [2;36m│[0m
[2;36m│[0m 2. **JSON body with any payload (including XSS)** → "Let the game begin. Good Luck"    [2;36m│[0m
[2;36m│[0m with NO reflection                                                                     [2;36m│[0m
[2;36m│[0m 3. **Form-urlencoded with special proto patterns** → Same "Good Luck" response         [2;36m│[0m
[2;36m│[0m                                                                                        [2;36m│[0m
[2;36m│[0m The JSON content-type bypasses the alert detection entirely! The response changes to   [2;36m│[0m
[2;36m│[0m the success state ("Let the game begin. Good Luck") and the input is not reflected.    [2;36m│[0m
[2;36m│[0m                                                                                        [2;36m│[0m
[2;36m│[0m However, the safe text with form-urlencoded still returns the error message. This      [2;36m│[0m
[2;36m│[0m confirms the protection is working but bypassable.                                     [2;36m│[0m
