[32m│[0m                                                                                        [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m ### thoughts                                                                           [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m The tests confirm that GET query parameters are not processed for reflection on either [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m `/` or `/page` endpoints. This means the only XSS attack surface is the POST `/page`   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m endpoint with the `solution` body parameter, which already has known protections. The  [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m application appears to strictly differentiate between GET (read-only, no user input    [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m reflection) and POST (form submission with input reflection). Future testing should    [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m focus on POST body bypasses and alternative encodings rather than GET-based            [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m approaches.                                                                            [32m│[0m
